\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Eddie stepped off the ferry first, tossing a few coins to the ferryman before helping Torrie down onto the sturdy wooden planks of Osthaven\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s dock. The air here was different\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 crisper, drier. Less of that thick, briny scent of fish that clung to Weshaven. Instead, the harbour was filled with the rich aromas of spice crates being unloaded, the earthy scent of dried herbs, and the occasional whiff of parchment and ink from merchants tallying their stock.}
\par\plain {Osthaven was busier in a different way. Where Weshaven had the steady rhythm of fishermen mending nets and unloading the morning\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s catch, Osthaven hummed with the brisk efficiency of trade. Men and women haggled over silk and spices from distant lands, warehouse workers hauled crates marked with foreign sigils, and couriers darted between carts carrying letters sealed with wax.}
\par\plain {Torrie took it all in, wide-eyed. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s\u8230\'85 bigger than I thought.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie smirked. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Told you. Less fish guts, more commerce.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {They moved through the streets, weaving past merchants arranging their displays and scholars in robes, their arms laden with books. As they walked, Eddie found his eyes drifting, the familiar streets pulling at old memories.}
\par\plain {As they walked through the bustling streets of Osthaven, Eddie gestured toward a small stall by the corner, where the scent of roasted chestnuts wafted through the air.}
\par\plain {"See that?" Eddie said, nudging Torrie. "Markus and I used to stop there after classes. We'd split a bag of chestnuts and complain about assignments the whole way home."}
\par\plain {Torrie looked over, her nose scrunching slightly. "You two really bonded over complaining, huh?"}
\par\plain {Eddie smirked. "It's an art form, I tell you."}
\par\plain {They continued down the road, past the colorful stalls of cloth merchants, until Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s gaze landed on a narrow shop with a faded green awning.}
\par\plain {"And that place," he pointed, "Was where I used to get supplies for my... projects."}
\par\plain {Torrie raised an eyebrow. "What kind of 'projects'?"}
\par\plain {Eddie chuckled. "Alchemy, mostly. The owner\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 grumpiest old man you'd ever meet\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 used to grumble about every single request I made, but he never actually turned me away."}
\par\plain {Torrie grinned. "Sounds like he liked you."}
\par\plain {Eddie scoffed, shaking his head. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I think he just liked my coins.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie slowed slightly, his fingers brushing against the strap of his bag. It was strange, being back. The town hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t changed much, but everything felt different now.}
\par\plain {Torrie noticed his lingering gaze. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ve been here a lot, huh?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie gave a small nod, exhaling softly. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yeah\u8230\'85 long ago.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Torrie smiled. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, now I\u8217\'92m here too.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie chuckled, shaking off the weight of nostalgia. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yeah. Let\u8217\'92s get you to Aella.\u8221\'94}
